# Obsidian Task Skills

Skills for managing tasks and daily journals in an Obsidian vault via MCP.

## Vault Location

Configure the vault path in your Obsidian MCP server (e.g., `~/Documents/MyVault/`).

## Task Frontmatter Template

All 9 fields are required on every task note:

```yaml
title: ""
status: ""        # open | doing | done | cancelled
priority: ""      # highest | high | medium | low
created_date: ""  # YYYY-MM-DD
due_date: ""
completed_date: ""
cancelled_date: ""
jira_link: ""
tags: []
```

## Filename Patterns

- Jira-linked: `{jira-key-lower}-{title-slug}.md` (e.g. `proj-123-fix-login-timeout.md`)
- Standalone: `{descriptive-slug}.md`
- All task notes live in the `tasks/` directory

## Journal Format

Journals live at `journals/YYYY-MM-DD.md`. The template has two sections:

```markdown
# YYYY-MM-DD

## Tasks:
- [ ] [[task-slug]]

## Notes:
-
```

- Some older journals use `Targets:` instead of `Tasks:` — preserve whichever header exists, don't rename it.
- The `Tasks:` section is owned by task skills (`task-create`, `task-daily`, `task-status`, `task-sync-jira`).
- The `Notes:` section is owned by `journal-note` (appending) and `journal-organize` (grouping into topic sub-sections).

## Journal Safety Rule

**NEVER use `write_note` on a journal file that already exists.** Journals accumulate user-written content throughout the day. Using `write_note` (mode `overwrite`) would destroy that content. Only use `patch_note` to modify existing journals. `write_note` is permitted ONLY when `read_note` confirms the journal does not exist yet.

## Jira Domain

By default, Jira links use `https://yourcompany.atlassian.net`. Update the domain in the skill files if your instance differs.

## Priority Mapping from Jira

| Jira priority | Obsidian priority |
|---------------|-------------------|
| Critical, Blocker | highest |
| Major | high |
| Medium, Normal | medium |
| Minor, Low, Trivial | low |
| (missing) | medium |

## Obsidian MCP Tool Gotchas

- `get_notes_info` returns file metadata only (size, modified date) — NOT frontmatter field values. Do not use it to read status, priority, etc.
- `search_notes` with `searchFrontmatter: true` does fuzzy text matching, not exact field matching. Do not use it to filter by specific frontmatter values — it returns false positives.
- `search_notes` is capped at `limit: 20` max results.
- `read_multiple_notes` accepts max 10 paths per call. Always pass `includeContent: false` when only frontmatter is needed.
- `patch_note` cannot replace with empty string — use a single space if needed.

**Reliable pattern:** Use `read_multiple_notes` (includeContent: false) in batches of 10, then filter in-memory. Do not pre-filter with `get_notes_info` or `search_notes`.
